A healthy outcome
Jeremy Hunt, the Health Secretary, must be brave, bold and radical in appointing Sir David Nicholson's successor at the NHS Sir David Nicholson, who has become embroiled in the Mid Staffs care scandal, will step down next year as chief executive of NHS England - and not before time By Telegraph View
7:44PM BST 21 May 2013
Comments
The news that Sir David Nicholson will step down next year as chief executive of NHS England has been greeted with the kind of tributes reserved for a deceased member of the Politburo – rather appropriately, given his prior association with the Communist Party of Great Britain. “Thanks to Sir David’s leadership,” effused Professor Malcolm Grant, the NHS’s chairman, “we are now in as good a position as we could be to take on the challenges that lie ahead.” Jeremy Hunt, the Health Secretary, paid tribute to his “relentless focus on what makes a difference on the NHS front line”.
The friends and family of the patients who died at Stafford Hospital would dispute that assertion, since the trust in question came under Sir David’s purview. There was also something alarming about ministers’ repeated insistence that Sir David must be retained despite that scandal, since he was the only person who could make the NHS’s unwieldy superstructure work efficiently. Our health service must be in a sorry state if it requires such a superman to keep it running.
This newspaper had hoped that Sir David would do the decent thing some time ago – but now that he is to retire, Mr Hunt is faced with the biggest decision of his career. As culture secretary, he had the chance to appoint the head of the BBC Trust (alighting on the familiar figure of Lord Patten). But now, under the NHS’s new, devolved structure, he must approve whichever candidate is selected by Prof Grant and his board to guide the health service through a period of wrenching change. The blueprint here must be the search for the Governor of the Bank of England, which eschewed the obvious and comfortable choices in favour of scouring the world for a top-class figure. Mr Hunt and Prof Grant must be brave, bold and radical – as must their appointee.
