The best mid-cap shares and funds We ask the experts to choose their favourite ways to invest in 'mid-caps', including funds, trusts and a drugs stock. BTG is a mid-cap share in Neptune's portfolio By Emma Wall
3:25PM GMT 11 Jan 2013
Follow Comments
Searching for the perfect balance between risk and reward? Fans of mid-cap equities say the sector offers just that. We asked financial professionals their preferred ways to get exposure to the mid-cap story. Investors should remember, however, that past performance is no indicator of future gains and that the value of investments – in particular share holdings – can go down as well as up. Shares Redrow Neptune mid-cap manager Mark Martin holds this house builder in his fund. He said the stock was well placed to benefit from increasing numbers of first-time buyers helped onto the property ladder by government-backed schemes. "Redrow's chairman and founder is Steve Morgan. Better known in some circles for his role as chairman of Wolverhampton Wanderers, Mr Morgan has been driving an impressive turnaround at Redrow," Mr Martin said. "The house building sector generally has benefited from expanding margins as builders start selling houses built on land bought at the bottom of the cycle. Morgan recently tried to take back control of Redrow with an opportunistic offer for the company. Although the offer has been rebuffed by shareholders, his interest is a clear signal of confidence in the fundamental value of the company."
