The company is currently trading at 170p a share and has not paid a dividend since 2008. EnQuest
Another stock in Mr Martin's portfolio is EnQuest, an oil production company focused on the North Sea. "It was formed in April 2010 when Petrofac span off some of its North Sea oilfields and the assets were combined with Lundin Petroleum oilfields," he said. "Senior management have long, successful experience from Petrofac days and the company is benefiting from the Government's desire to incentivise investment in the North Sea."
The company is currently trading at 126p a share and does not pay a dividend. BTG BTG is a health care company developing some promising new drugs – including one for prostate cancer, which was the most successful oral oncology launch ever – and a revolutionary drug for varicose veins. It will also be a beneficiary of a government scheme called the "Patent Box", due to be phased in from April, which will enable companies to apply a lower rate of corporation tax to profits earned from patented inventions. "The Government is incentivising science, and research and development," said Mr Martin. "I think this will be an interesting investment theme for 2013 and beyond."
The company's shares currently trade at 341p but it does not pay a dividend. Funds Old Mutual UK Select Mid Cap This fund has returned 32.4pc over the past 12 months and 49pc over the past three years. "Richard Watts, the manager, is focusing on areas that can grow despite weakness in the wider economy," said Mark Dampier of Hargreaves Lansdown. "One current theme is the technology sector, where the fund has large positions in Telecity and Aveva. This fund remains a good choice for exposure to mid-cap stocks." It has a yield of 0.5pc and an annual charge of 1.5pc. Throgmorton Trust John Newlands of Brewin Dolphin tipped this investment trust, which is substantially exposed to mid-cap companies despite being in the industry's UK Smaller Companies sector. "Managed by BlackRock's Mike Prentis and Richard Plackett, the trust stands on a useful discount of around 13pc to net asset value and has produced a total return of more than 90pc over the past three years," Mr Newlands said. It has a yield of 1.48pc and an annual charge of 0.7pc, on top of which there is a performance fee. Standard Life UK Smaller Companies "This is one of my strongest recommendations on a medium or longer-term view. Again it has a significant proportion of its holdings in the FTSE 250, as well as in smaller cap and Aim stocks," said Mr Newlands. "Run by Harry Nimmo, I consider this trust worth buying even though it is trading on a premium." The investment trust has a yield of 1.5pc and an annual charge of 1.6pc. Schroder UK Mid Cap investment trust This Schroder fund is currently trading at a discount, although it has limited gearing and a highly capable manager. It has returned 46pc in the past 12 months, outperforming the top unit trust in the sector. Investors who bought three years ago would have seen returns of 82pc. It is heavily exposed to the industrial companies sector, with house builders and pharmaceuticals featuring in the top 10 holdings. Wealth manager Philippa Gee tipped the fund, but warned about its performance fee – equivalent to 0.1pc for every 1pc rise – so don't use this for a low-cost play. HSBC FTSE 250 Index Tracker For a cheap option, Ms Gee recommended the HSBC FTSE 250 Index Tracker fund, which offers exposure to the entire mid-cap index and has a total annual charge of 0.27pc. Featured Isa / Investment platforms »
