Divorcing partners 'take out anger on each other using the courts'
Divorcing couples are taking out their anger on their former partner using the courts, a watchdog warned, as it said setting realistic objectives could cut legal fees from £50,000 to £10,000.
Nearly one in five of the 7,500 complaints resolved last year were about divorce or family law-related cases Photo: ALAMY	By Wesley Johnson, Home Affairs Correspondent
6:00AM GMT 28 Feb 2013
One unemployed mother was charged £4,000 for photocopying alone by her divorce lawyer while other bills exceeded divorcees' expectations by more than £30,000, a study of legal complaints found.
Time spent by lawyers “lending a supportive ear and corresponding with the other side soon mounts up”, the report said.
Adam Sampson, the chief legal ombudsman, said: "Some customers also create their own problems by letting emotions take over in the divorce process.”
The report, the Price of Separation, found: “One of the reasons why costs can spiral out of control lies in the emotional rawness of many of those going through divorce proceedings.
“Divorce is often a lonely time, where someone is facing very real uncertainties and taking important decisions, yet in a state of deep emotion. Related Articles
Businessman loses divorce bid after map-reading row
25 Feb 2013
Weston-super-Mare 'is divorce hotspot'
20 Feb 2013
“In those circumstances, it is common for people to become inflexible or change their minds (and thus their instructions) during the divorce process. “It is also common for them to rely heavily on the one individual who is both an expert in how to negotiate the process and who is seen to be on their side: their lawyer.”
It added: “As hard as it must be to keep emotions in check, the lessons from this report all point towards the necessity for divorcing couples to try.”
In one of the most “standout” cases, a mother-of-one, who had been made redundant, asked her lawyers to halt proceedings but they continued regardless and hit her with a £15,000 bill. The woman - known as Miss A - brought her complaint to the Ombudsman, which agreed the firm should waive the final bill and ordered it to do so. The study revealed that nearly one in five of the 7,500 complaints resolved last year were about divorce or family law-related cases, making it the most complained about area of law in England and Wales.
